    "body": "Interesting, will have to take a look. I know Solidity has special fixed-size byte arrays called `bytes1`, `bytes2`, ..., `bytes31` and `bytes32`, but there is also the dynamically sized `bytes` type.\r\n\r\nIt looks like Viper always compiles it to `bytes`.\r\n\r\nAccording to the [`to_abi_dict`](https://github.com/ethereum/viper/blob/master/viper/function_signature.py#L90) method, the [`canonicalize_type`](https://github.com/ethereum/viper/blob/master/viper/types.py#L128) method is used to determine the type of an input/output, and that method *always* returns `bytes` for the `ByteArrayType`, even though an instance of that class has a `maxlen` attribute.\r\n\r\nIf the ABI stays consistent with the Solidity one, then you could simply check the `maxlen` attribute (if it's less than 32), and set the appropriate number accordingly:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nif isinstance(t, ByteArrayType):\r\n    if t.maxlen <= 32:\r\n        return 'bytes%d' % t.maxlen\r\n    else:\r\n        return 'bytes'\r\n```",
